{
  "texts": [
    "Very common are those focusing on social media or microblogging texts (CREDBANK (Mitra and Gilbert 2015), MEDIAEVAL15 (Boididou et al. 2015), WEIBO15 (Ma et al. 2016), WEIBO17 (Jin et al. 2017), WECHAT (Wang et al. 2020)).",
    "Another common domain involves celebrity rumors, typically annotated for verification rather than veracity, and also commonly sourced from social media posts (WEB DATASET CELEBRITY (Pérez-Rosas et al. 2018), FAKENEWSNET/GOSSIPCOP (Shu et al. 2019)).",
    "During the COVID-19 pandemic, various health-related datasets were introduced (FAKEHEALTH (Dai, Sun, and Wang 2020), MM-COVID (Li et al. 2020), FAKECOVID (Shahi and Nandini 2020), COAID (Cui and Lee 2020)).",
    "In this subsection, we discuss how specific operationalizations can introduce bias in the dataset, adversely affecting model generalization performance.",
    "Differing Definitions."
  ]
}